 offer insight into how race and class co-produced one another and how boundaries fundamental to settler colonialism were regulated and policed. Based on original research conducted in Zimbabwe, South Africa and the UK, this book offers a unique theoretical synthesis of work on gender, whiteness studies, labour histories, settler colonialism, Marxism, emotions and the New African Economic History.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSocial classeszZimbabwexHistory. 0aWhite peoplexRace identityzZimbabwe. 0aWhite peoplezZimbabwexHistory. 0aWorking class whitesxSocial conditionsxHistoryzZimbabwe. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2021. 7aHISTORY / Africa / South / General.2bisacsh  aMarxism.  aRhodesia.  aZimbabwe.  aclass.  agender.  anationalism.  arace.  asettler.  awhiteness.  awork.1 aGinsburgh, Nicola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614388440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526143884423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526143884/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles